  <h2>Andover's Market: Higher-End Homes, Different Seller Situations</h2>
  <p>Andover's different from most of the metro. It's more affluent, newer (mostly 1990s forward), and homes are typically $250k-$500k+. The USD 385 school district is a major draw, which means family stability, but it also means when someone needs to sell, there's usually a real reason and a time crunch. Divorce. Corporate relocation. Estate situations where heirs live out of state.</p>
  <p>These are quality homes in good shape. Nobody's buying a $350k house in Andover to tear off the roof. That changes the conversation. I'm not buying a distressed property that needs $40k in work — I'm buying a good house from someone who has a life change and needs liquidity fast.</p>

  <h2>Andover Housing Market: Quality, Equity, and Timeline Pressure</h2>
  <p>Andover homes hold value well because they're newer, well-maintained, and in high-demand school district areas. You're looking at $250k-$500k+ for most properties. The housing stock is mostly 1990s-2020s — newer construction, good systems, move-in-ready condition. Andover doesn't have the foundation issues or aging roof problems that plague older Wichita neighborhoods.</p>
  <p>The seller situations are what's interesting. Parents who moved to Andover in the 1990s for the schools are now retired or passing, and their kids don't want the house. Corporate relocations happen here because of Kansas City and Dallas proximity — people getting transferred for jobs. Divorce situations in Andover involve real equity — not "we're splitting a $120k house," but "how do we divide a $350k asset quickly."</p>

  <h2>Who I Buy From in Andover</h2>
  <p>High-net-worth divorce situations. Andover attracts successful professionals, and when marriages end, the house is often the biggest asset. They want clean, quick liquidation. Estate sales from original buyers moving into retirement communities. Corporate relocations — people who bought thinking they'd be here 20 years, now they're moving to Dallas or Kansas City for a promotion. Heirs who inherited property they don't want to manage. People building a bigger house and need to sell the current one quickly to fund the move.</p>
  <p>These aren't distressed sellers usually. They're sellers with equity, decent homes, and a timeline. They want fair value and speed, not a six-month listing process.</p>

